ponse and making treatment choices. Charles Manski addresses the treatment-choice problem directly using Abraham Wald's statistical decision theory, taking into account the ambiguity that arises from identification problems under weak but justifiable assumptions. The book unifies and further develops the influential line of research the author began in the late 1990s. It will be a valuable resource to researchers and upper-level graduate students in economics as well as other social sciences, statistics, epidemiology and related areas of public health, and operations research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEstimation theory. 0aSocial choice. 0aSocial sciencesxStatistical methods. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / General.2bisacsh  a"Objective Function.  aBayes Rules.  aBinary Covariates.  aBounding Expected Welfare.  aConcave Monotonicity.  aCovariate Information.  aEmpirical Success Rules.  aHoeffding theorem.  aHypothesis Testing.  aMaximin Criterion.  aNonutilitarian Objective Functions.  aOptimal Treatment Rule.  aSemi-Monotone Response.  aSentencing.  aSocial Interactions.  aUntenable Assumptions.  aconditional empirical success.  aexternal validity.  ainstrumental variable.  aquasi-optimal".  ashrinkage estimators.  avariable selection procedures.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691217734zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691217734423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691217734.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  